		 	<span id="comment_score_64605409" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64605409); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~quantaman">quantaman</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~quantaman">( 517394 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64605409"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64605409"><p><div class="quote"><p>As a former cancer patient who was given the choice between foregoing a few bits or trying limb salvage with a risk that the big C might not be rid of totally, I didn't hesitate for more than a couple seconds: chop-chop Doc, I'll deal with the inconveniences later. If I'm dead, what good will it do me if I go to my grave four-limbed?</p><p>That's a bummer for the lady, but she can already get her breast reconstructed later. It might not be perfect or as good a reconstruction as if she had had it done on the spot, but she will be alive. Priorities... Trust me on that one.</p></div><p>I don't think the point of the story was that she had trouble making the decision.</p><p>Instead it's the consequences of the ransomware attack, typically it's "stuff was chaotic and someone died, but they might have died anyways".</p><p>This is one of the few cases where they can draw a direct line between a ransomware attack and a clear adverse health outcome.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64605409">

