		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64605153" name="comment_link_64605153" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23378953&amp;cid=64605153" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64605153)" >I worked in Hospital IT</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64605153" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64605153); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>1</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~n0w0rries">n0w0rries</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~n0w0rries">( 832057 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64605153"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64605153"><p>I worked for a hospital in California doing their IT. I consolidated their 40+ servers down to 6 with a fault tolerant cluster solution. Downtime was a PITA, because even at 2am they would get the drunk rush of patients in the ER.</p><p>The hospital was supposed to be able to run on paper. They didn't like to do it, but it was doable. Any business that is 100% reliant on computers to function is going to be f-ed sooner or later.</p><p>I got out of the field, but I remember telling my clients "Don't move your stuff to the<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64605153">

</div>
